<hl>
<seg id=1> Chinese Building Materials Industry Sees Foreign Cooperation Developing Quickly </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> XINHUA NEWS AGENCY WIRE Beijing, March 19 (Li Jianmin reporting):  The building materials industry in China sees the improvement of foreign cooperation as an important means of speeding up development. The realm of foreign investment is expanding quickly, and at present the whole industry has attracted up to 5 billion U.S. dollars from outside the country. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> An official with the National Building Materials Bureau revealed during an interview today that China's building materials industry is currently using money from the World Bank and the Bank of Asia to perform, in succession, large concrete construction projects in Tongling in Anhui province and Xiangxiang in Hunan province. </seg>
<seg id=4> Foreign investment is quickly developing new forms of building materials, new technology and finely-processed building materials. </seg>
<seg id=5> In Shaanxi, Shandong, Guangdong, Jilin and Hunan provinces, preferred export credit from Italy in the amount of 100 million U.S. dollars is being used to develop a high quality retrofit bathroom ceramics products. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Recently, the Chinese building materials industry has signed bilateral agreements with government departments and multinational corporations from the Netherlands, Germany, Thailand, Greece, Australia, Japan, France and Denmark. There has been a large increase in the number of foreign partners in this field. </seg>
<seg id=7> Last year foreign exchange earned from Chinese building materials products exports exceeded 2.1 billion U.S. dollars. Cement exports of 12 million tons, an increase of 46 percent over the previous year, were the highest in history. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> China has also adopted precalcining kiln production technology in the last few years, establishing modern large-scale cement companies such as Jidong, Ningguo, Zhunhai and Liuzhou. Their annual cement production has increased by 22 million tons. </seg>
</p>
